**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**
Graph Structure Learning (GSL) and Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) are powerful tools for analyzing graph-structured data, but they face challenges when dealing with noisy and sparse graph structures. Leveraging large language models (LLMs) can enhance the robustness and accuracy of these models by incorporating rich textual data associated with nodes.

**Here are the five core questions:**

**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**
How can we refine graph structures in the presence of noisy and sparse data using large language models (LLMs) to improve the performance of Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)?

**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**
Solving this problem is crucial for advancing the reliability and applicability of GNNs in real-world scenarios where graph data is often incomplete or noisy. This research will lead to more robust models that can handle data imperfections, enhancing their performance in various domains such as social networks, recommender systems, and epidemiological predictions.

**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**
The challenge lies in effectively integrating textual data into graph structures and developing algorithms that can accurately identify and address noisy connections. Naive approaches may fail due to the complexity of capturing implicit dependencies and the high dimensionality of textual data.

**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**
Previous research has focused on explicit graph structures and has not fully leveraged the potential of textual data. The integration of LLMs into GSL is a relatively new and unexplored area, requiring novel methodologies and techniques.

**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**
The proposed methodology involves developing a model called GraphEdit that uses LLMs to generate embeddings for node attributes and incorporates these embeddings into GNNs. The model will be evaluated on various datasets with noisy and sparse graph structures, using metrics such as accuracy, robustness, and interpretability to measure its performance. Expected outcomes include a more robust and accurate GNN that can handle real-world data imperfections.

