ults.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused primarily on explicit graph structures and has not fully explored the potential of integrating textual data. The technical and theoretical challenges involved in effectively combining GNNs and LLMs have prevented this problem from being solved until now.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a model called GraphEdit, which leverages large language models to refine graph structures by processing textual data associated with nodes. The methodology includes using a combination of GNNs and LLMs, training on a dataset with both explicit and implicit graph structures, and evaluating the results using metrics such as accuracy, robustness, and interpretability. The expected outcomes include a more robust and accurate graph learning framework that can handle noisy and sparse data effectively.\n\n**Methodology:**\n- **Data Collection:** Gather a dataset with both explicit graph structures and textual data associated with nodes. This dataset will be used to train and evaluate the GraphEdit model.\n- **Model Development:** Develop the GraphEdit model, which combines GNNs and LLMs. The GNN will process the graph structure, while the LLM will process the textual data. The outputs from both models will be integrated to refine the graph structure.\n- **Training and Evaluation:** Train the GraphEdit model on the dataset and evaluate its performance using metrics such as accuracy, robustness, and interpretability. The model will be tested on both synthetic and real-world datasets to ensure its effectiveness.\n\n**Expected Outcomes:**\n- A more robust and accurate graph learning framework that can handle noisy and sparse data effectively.\n- Improved performance in downstream tasks, such as node classification and link prediction.\n- A deeper understanding of the integration of textual data into graph learning processes.\n\n**Timeline:**\n- **Month 1-2:** Data collection and preprocessing.\n- **Month 3-4:** Model development and initial training.\n- **Month 5-6:** Model evaluation and refinement.\n- **Month 7-8:** Final testing and documentation.\n- **Month 9:** Preparation for presentation or submission.\n\n**Resources:**\n- Computational resources for training and evaluating the model.\n- Datasets with both explicit graph structures and textual data.\n- Funding for research activities and resources.\n\n### Next Steps\n- Share the draft of the research proposal with peers or mentors for feedback.\n- Incorporate any suggestions or criticisms to improve the proposal.\n- Format the proposal according to the guidelines of the intended audience.\n- Prepare a presentation or summary if the proposal needs to be presented to a team or stakeholders.\n- Secure necessary resources for the research project.\n\nThis refined proposal is now ready for further feedback and finalization.\n"}, {'agent2': "Result from the model:To refine the research proposal based on the 5Q format, I will ensure that each question is clear, concise, and well-structured. I will also address any potential gaps or weaknesses in the proposed approach. Here is the refined version of the research proposal:\n\n---\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nGraph Structure Learning (GSL) and Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) are powerful tools for analyzing graph-structured data, but they face significant challenges when dealing with noisy and sparse graph structures. Leveraging large language models (LLMs) to refine graph structures can enhance the accuracy and robustness of these models.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we refine graph structures in the presence of noisy and sparse data to improve the accuracy and robustness of graph neural networks?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this 