oposal.\n'}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can large language models (LLMs) be effectively integrated with graph neural networks (GNNs) to refine graph structures in the presence of noisy and sparse data?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem is crucial for advancing graph structure learning, especially in real-world applications where data imperfections are common. It will enable more robust and accurate graph representations, leading to improved performance in downstream tasks such as node classification and recommendation systems. This research will also pave the way for integrating rich textual data into graph learning frameworks, opening up new avenues for research and practical applications.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "Integrating LLMs with GNNs to refine graph structures is challenging due to the need for seamless interaction between text and graph data. Naive approaches may fail to effectively capture the complex dependencies and relationships within the graph. Technical obstacles include aligning textual embeddings with graph structures, handling high-dimensional data, and ensuring computational efficiency. Theoretical challenges involve developing novel methods for co-optimization and dynamic graph structure learning. Practical obstacles include the availability of labeled datasets and the need for scalable algorithms.",\n\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has primarily focused on using explicit graph structures as supervision signals, which can be unreliable in noisy and sparse environments. Existing methods often lack the ability to effectively integrate textual data into graph learning frameworks. The integration of LLMs with GNNs for dynamic graph structure refinement is a relatively unexplored area, with limited prior work addressing these specific challenges. Our approach aims to bridge this gap by leveraging the strengths of both LLMs and GNNs.",\n\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "Our proposed methodology involves developing a model called GraphEdit, which integrates LLMs to generate refined graph structures. The key components include: (1) using LLMs to generate embeddings for node attributes, (2) integrating these embeddings into GNNs, and (3) refining graph structures through co-optimization. We will use datasets such as subsets of the Facebook dataset, MovieLens dataset, and disease spread simulation data. Evaluation metrics will include accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score for node classification tasks. Expected outcomes include improved graph representations and enhanced performance in downstream tasks, demonstrating the effectiveness of our approach in handling noisy and sparse data."\n}\n```', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': [], 'total_milestones': 0, 'agent_kpis': {}}], 'planning_scores': [-1, -1, -1], 'communication_scores': [-1, -1, -1], 'token_usage': 113733, 'agent_kpis': {}, 'total_milestones': 0, 'task_evaluation': {'innovation': 4, 'safety': 4, 'feasibility': 3}}
